# Tech Stack
- Framework: Next.js 16+ with App Router
- Language: TypeScript (strict mode)
- UI Library: Material UI (MUI) v5+
- Styling: Emotion (via MUI sx prop and styled()) + vanilla CSS where appropriate
- Sliders/Carousels: Swiper.js
- Key paths: src/app/ (routes), src/components/ (reusable UI), src/theme.ts (MUI theme)

---

## DESIGN SYSTEM RULES

### Theme (src/theme.ts)
- All colors MUST be defined in the MUI theme — never hardcode hex values inline
- Define a complete palette: primary, secondary, error, warning, success, info
- Define custom tokens for: background.default, background.paper, text.primary, text.secondary
- Support both light and dark mode via MUI's createTheme with palette.mode
- Typography scale must cover: h1–h6, body1, body2, caption, overline, button
- Define custom breakpoints if default MUI ones (xs/sm/md/lg/xl) are not sufficient
- Export the theme as a default export and import it once at the root layout

### Spacing & Layout
- Use MUI's spacing system (theme.spacing()) for all margins and paddings — never use arbitrary px values
- Use MUI Grid2 (not legacy Grid) for all responsive layouts
- Maintain 8px base unit throughout
- Max content width: 1200px, centered with mx: 'auto'

### Typography
- Pair a display/heading font with a body font (define both in theme.ts via MUI's typography.fontFamily)
- Heading sizes must scale properly on mobile: use responsive typography (e.g., { xs: '1.5rem', md: '2.5rem' })
- Line height for body text: 1.6–1.75

### Colors
- Minimum contrast ratio: 4.5:1 for body text, 3:1 for large text (WCAG AA)
- Never use pure black (#000000) — use a near-black from the palette instead
- Accent color should appear sparingly: CTA buttons, highlights, active states only

---

## COMPONENT RULES

### Reusability
- Every UI element used more than once MUST be extracted into src/components/
- Component props must be typed with TypeScript interfaces — never use `any`
- Components must accept and forward a `sx` prop for MUI style overrides when appropriate
- Use composition over configuration: prefer small, focused components over large multi-purpose ones

### Component File Structure
Each component file should follow this pattern:
```tsx
// src/components/ProjectCard/ProjectCard.tsx
interface ProjectCardProps { ... }
export const ProjectCard = ({ ... }: ProjectCardProps) => { ... }
export default ProjectCard
```

### Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., SkillBadge, ProjectCard, SectionHeader)
- Files: match component name (ProjectCard.tsx)
- Hooks: useXxx pattern (e.g., useScrollPosition)
- Types/interfaces: PascalCase with suffix (e.g., ProjectCardProps, SkillItem)

---

## RESPONSIVE DESIGN RULES

- Mobile-first approach: design for xs first, then scale up with MUI breakpoints
- Every layout must be tested at: 375px, 768px, 1024px, 1440px
- Use MUI's useMediaQuery hook for conditional logic — never use CSS media queries in JS
- Images: always use Next.js <Image /> with proper width, height, and alt attributes
- Touch targets: minimum 44x44px for all interactive elements on mobile
- Navigation: must collapse to hamburger/drawer on mobile (sm breakpoint)

---

## TESTING RULES

- Unit tests: use Jest + React Testing Library for all components in src/components/
- Each component must have at minimum:
  - A smoke test (renders without crashing)
  - A test for each user-visible state (loading, empty, error, success)
  - A test for key interactive behaviors (click, hover if relevant)
- Accessibility: use jest-axe in tests to catch a11y violations automatically
- File convention: ComponentName.test.tsx co-located with the component
- Run tests with: npm test — all tests must pass before committing

---

## CODE QUALITY RULES

- TypeScript: strict mode enabled, no `as any` casts, no implicit `any`
- No inline styles (style={{...}}) — use sx prop or styled() from MUI/Emotion
- No unused imports, variables, or components
- All async operations must handle loading and error states
- Use Next.js Server Components by default; add 'use client' only when necessary (event handlers, hooks, browser APIs)
- Environment variables: prefix with NEXT_PUBLIC_ for client-side, never expose secrets

---

## FILE & IMPORT CONVENTIONS

- Absolute imports via tsconfig paths: @/components/..., @/theme, @/types/...
- Group imports: React → Next.js → MUI → local components → types → styles
- Barrel exports: each component folder should have an index.ts
